00:00:49,984 --> 00:00:52,718
narrator: paper umbrellas originated in china       

4
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:55,253
and eventually spread throughout asia.         

5
00:00:55,255 --> 00:00:58,190
initially, their purpose was solely practical --     

6
00:00:58,192 --> 00:00:59,725
to protect against rain     

7
00:00:59,727 --> 00:01:02,461
and to provide shade from the scorching sun.     

8
00:01:02,463 --> 00:01:05,932
but before long, they took on symbolic significance      

9
00:01:05,934 --> 00:01:09,635
and were incorporated into many ceremonies and rituals.   

10
00:01:12,540 --> 00:01:15,407
they're called oil paper umbrellas       

11
00:01:15,409 --> 00:01:17,910
because the paper is coated with oil        

12
00:01:17,912 --> 00:01:20,145
or, like these, with oil paint,             

13
00:01:20,147 --> 00:01:23,749
making the umbrella waterproof.           

14
00:01:23,751 --> 00:01:26,352
at this workshop in northern thailand,      

15
00:01:26,354 --> 00:01:29,088
they cut a bamboo log to the length          

16
00:01:29,090 --> 00:01:30,556
of the umbrella's radius,    

17
00:01:30,558 --> 00:01:32,491
then shave off the bark.     

18
00:01:32,493 --> 00:01:37,696
they split the log into strips of equal thickness,       

19
00:01:37,698 --> 00:01:39,298
then group these ribs, as they're called,        

20
00:01:39,300 --> 00:01:41,299
into bundles of 28.       

21
00:01:41,301 --> 00:01:45,303
each bundle will become the frame of one umbrella.    

22
00:01:45,305 --> 00:01:47,974
next, they thin out the bottom half of each rib   

23
00:01:47,976 --> 00:01:49,976
and cut a slit in the top half.              

24
00:01:49,978 --> 00:01:52,511
then, using a traditional drill,             

25
00:01:52,513 --> 00:01:57,983
they bore            
tiny holes at specific points.  

26
00:01:57,985 --> 00:02:00,118
taking one bundle at a time,   

27
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:03,588
they string the ribs together through the uppermost hole    

28
00:02:03,590 --> 00:02:07,259
and insert them into slots of a hand-carved wooden hub.   

29
00:02:07,261 --> 00:02:09,995
then they tighten and tie off the string            

30
00:02:09,997 --> 00:02:13,265
to retain the ribs in position and provide a pivot       

31
00:02:13,267 --> 00:02:15,233
on which the ribs can move up and down.           

32
00:02:15,235 --> 00:02:18,204
next, they attach the scaffold,            

33
00:02:18,206 --> 00:02:21,874
a smaller hub with shorter ribs strung on it.               

34
00:02:21,876 --> 00:02:26,345
they insert a scaffold rib into the slit of each frame rib,              

35
00:02:26,347 --> 00:02:28,147
then attach them by threading a string             

36
00:02:28,149 --> 00:02:30,549
through the aligned holes.    

37
00:02:30,551 --> 00:02:31,751
the result?           

38
00:02:31,753 --> 00:02:33,552
raising and lowering the scaffold           

39
00:02:33,554 --> 00:02:36,555
moves its ribs along the slit --               

40
00:02:36,557 --> 00:02:39,891
pushing the frame ribs up to open the umbrella,      

41
00:02:39,893 --> 00:02:42,294
or pulling them down to close it.           

42
00:02:42,296 --> 00:02:45,630
with the umbrella open now,   

43
00:02:45,632 --> 00:02:49,034
they thread more string through holes in the frame ribs              

44
00:02:49,036 --> 00:02:51,637
and loop it into a spider-web-type pattern.    

45
00:02:51,639 --> 00:02:53,839
this produces a sturdy base   

46
00:02:53,841 --> 00:02:56,642
to support the umbrella's paper skin.    

47
00:02:56,644 --> 00:02:58,844
after mounting the frame     

48
00:02:58,846 --> 00:03:00,846
on a wood and bamboo umbrella handle,         

49
00:03:00,848 --> 00:03:05,050
they wrap two lines of string along the frame perimeter.    

50
00:03:05,052 --> 00:03:08,120
this will support the paper skin at the edge of the umbrella.   

51
00:03:08,122 --> 00:03:11,524
they make the paper from the bark of the native saa tree.              

52
00:03:11,526 --> 00:03:14,193
the first step is to soften the bark      

53
00:03:14,195 --> 00:03:16,862
by soaking it in water for about 12 hours,       

54
00:03:16,864 --> 00:03:19,365
then boiling it for another three or four.    

55
00:03:22,003 --> 00:03:24,804
next, they mash it with wooden mallets       

56
00:03:24,806 --> 00:03:27,073
for about an hour, turning it into pulp.      

57
00:03:30,278 --> 00:03:33,546
they bleach the pulp and wash it again to remove the bleach.   

58
00:03:33,548 --> 00:03:37,216
only then is the pulp ready to become paper.         

59
00:03:40,487 --> 00:03:43,489
they dump the pulp in a large basin of water    

60
00:03:43,491 --> 00:03:45,825
and stir so that it floats in suspension           

61
00:03:45,827 --> 00:03:48,961
while they move a plastic screen through the water,        

62
00:03:48,963 --> 00:03:50,830
catching enough floating pulp  

63
00:03:50,832 --> 00:03:53,065
to coat the screen in a thin layer.         

64
00:03:55,503 --> 00:03:57,903
they lay the screen out in the sun          

65
00:03:57,905 --> 00:03:59,437
for three to four hours     

66
00:03:59,439 --> 00:04:00,839
until the layer of pulp     

67
00:04:00,841 --> 00:04:04,242
dries into a thin, fragile sheet of paper.            

68
00:04:04,244 --> 00:04:07,045
they cut the sheets to the shapes required,     

69
00:04:07,047 --> 00:04:10,649
then saturate each piece with glue made from cassava,   

70
00:04:10,651 --> 00:04:12,451
a tropical root vegetable.    

71
00:04:12,453 --> 00:04:15,654
after applying a circular piece around the hub,         

72
00:04:15,656 --> 00:04:19,058
they glue pie-shaped pieces onto the rest of the frame.   

73
00:04:22,396 --> 00:04:25,463
once they cover the entire frame,        

74
00:04:25,465 --> 00:04:29,134
they repeat the process to add a second layer.      

75
00:04:29,136 --> 00:04:31,136
they fold all the pie-shaped pieces    

76
00:04:31,138 --> 00:04:32,538
over the end to thicken     

77
00:04:32,540 --> 00:04:35,808
and, thereby, reinforce the edge of the umbrella.    

78
00:04:35,810 --> 00:04:40,212
after about four hours out in the sun, the glue dries,             

79
00:04:40,214 --> 00:04:42,881
bonding the now stiff and strengthened paper      

80
00:04:42,883 --> 00:04:44,683
securely to the frame.      

81
00:04:44,685 --> 00:04:48,220
they apply three coats of oil paint,    

82
00:04:48,222 --> 00:04:51,891
allowing four hours of drying time between coats.  

83
00:04:51,893 --> 00:04:53,359
this is a key step        

84
00:04:53,361 --> 00:04:56,428
because aside from providing the background color,      

85
00:04:56,430 --> 00:04:59,231
the oil paint waterproofs the paper.            

86
00:04:59,233 --> 00:05:02,234
next, they varnish the handle  
to make it moisture-resistant.  

87
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:08,039
and now for the grand finale --               

88
00:05:08,041 --> 00:05:13,511
an artist paints a design in vibrant waterproof oils.   

89
00:05:13,513 --> 00:05:16,047
the themes are traditional --  

90
00:05:16,049 --> 00:05:21,854
flowers, animals, landscapes, people.       

91
00:05:21,856 --> 00:05:25,790
no stencils to trace or patterns to follow --     

92
00:05:25,792 --> 00:05:29,127
the artist works entirely freehand,        

93
00:05:29,129 --> 00:05:31,529
the result being that no two umbrellas      

94
00:05:31,531 --> 00:05:33,499
are ever exactly alike.     

95
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:39,872
each oil paper umbrella is a portable work of art.    

96
00:05:39,874 --> 00:05:44,777
pretty yet practical, rain or shine.          

